🤖 **What I Learned About Large Language Models (LLMs)**

📌 **Next-Word Prediction**
LLMs work by predicting the next word (token) based on the previous context.

📌 **Before Transformers**
Earlier language models processed text sequentially, one token at a time, making training slower and less efficient.

📌 **Transformer Architecture**
Google introduced the Transformer architecture in 2017, allowing models to process all input tokens in parallel during training, making them significantly faster and more scalable.

📌 **Attention Mechanism**
Attention helps the model identify which words in the input are most relevant, enabling it to better understand context before predicting the next token.

📌 **Forward Pass**
During training, the model performs a forward pass to predict the next token.

📌 **Backpropagation**
The prediction is compared with the correct answer, and backpropagation updates billions of parameters (weights) to reduce errors.

📌 **Pre-training**
The model learns language patterns by training on massive amounts of text from books, articles, websites, and other sources.

📌 **RLHF (Reinforcement Learning with Human Feedback)**
After pre-training, human feedback helps fine-tune the model to generate more helpful, safe, and natural responses.

📌 **Emergent Behavior**
Many impressive LLM capabilities aren't explicitly programmed—they emerge naturally as the model learns from large-scale data.

